<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900907-0102</DOCNO><DOCID>900907-0102.</DOCID><HL>   Kawasaki Heavy Industries   To Make Part of Airbus Jet   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>09/07/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   J.KWH F.ABI U.BA</CO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)AIRLINES (AIR)</IN><LP>   TOKYO -- Japan's Kawasaki Heavy Industries Co. willproduce part of the A-321 passenger jet being developed byEuropean airplane manufacturing consortium Airbus Industrie,a Kawasaki official said.   An official contract will be signed in mid-October betweenKawasaki and British Aerospace PLC, one of Airbus Industrie'sparent companies which makes bodies for Airbus airplanes.</LP><TEXT>   The A-321 jet, a long-bodied passenger jet still underdevelopment, is scheduled for test flight in the spring of1993 and marketing in the spring of 1994. There are more than100 orders for the new jet so far, according to the official.   The new plane, with a capacity of 180 passengers, will bemade by extending the body of the company's A-320 jet on bothends by a total of 7 meters.   Kawasaki will be the sole producer of skin panels to beattached to the A-320's tail end.   Details of the agreement are under negotiation, theofficial said.   The latest agreement is part of Kawasaki's businessstrategy aimed at increasing sales in its private sectordivision to reduce the company's dependency on theSelf-Defense Agency of Japan.   Demand by the agency is expected to decline in comingyears due to a world-wide trend toward disarmament. Ordersfor Kawasaki's P3C anti-submarine patrol planes, for example,are likely to fall more than 30% in the next fiscal year, theofficial said.</TEXT></DOC>